{{hatnote|This article is about the Arabic title. For the Hebrew title, see [[Messiah]]. For the Greek title, see [[Christ (title)]]. For Jesus of Nazareth, see [[Jesus]]. For the Islamic theological concept of the messiah, see [[Islamic messianism]]. For other uses, see [[Masih (disambiguation)]].}}
The '''Masih''' is the [[Arabic language|Arabic]] translation of the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] title [[messiah]], meaning "the anointed one".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Tanagho|first1=Samy|title=Glad News!: God Loves You, My Muslim Friend!|date=2017|publisher=Moody Publishers|isbn=9780802495778|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xs9uDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT78&dq=Masih+title&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGoILkl7bZAhUJS2MKHWm9BQMQ6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=Masih%20title&f=false|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref> It is used as a title for [[Jesus]] by both [[Muslim]]s and [[Arab Christian|Arabic speaking Christians]], because they believe him to be the prophesied [[Messiah in Judaism|Jewish messiah]] of the [[Hebrew Bible]]. He is also commonly known as the [[Christ (title)|Christ]], which is the [[Greek language|Greek]] translation of messiah.<ref name="McDowWalk2013">{{cite news|last1=McDowell|first1=Josh|last2=Walker|first2=Jim|title=Understanding Islam and Christianity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UfvgAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT16&dq=Masih+title&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGoILkl7bZAhUJS2MKHWm9BQMQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=Masih%20title&f=false|accessdate=21 February 2018|publisher=Harvest House Publishers|date=2013}}</ref> Both [[Christian]]s and [[Muslim]]s believe Jesus to be the messiah of the Hebrew Bible.<ref name="McDowWalk2013"/> Similarly, Masih is used by Arabic speaking Jews to refer to the [[messiah in Judaism|concept of the messiah in Judaism]].
