{{Jainism}}
King '''Nabhi''' or '''Nabhi Rai''' was the 14th or the last ''[[Kulakara]]'' of ''avasarpini''. He was the father of [[Rishabhanatha]], the first ''[[Tirthankara]]'' of present ''avasarpini''.

== Biography ==
King Nabhi or Nabhi Rai was the fourteenth or the last ''[[Kulakara]]''{{refn|group=note|According to [[Jain cosmology]], when the third ''ara'' of the ''avasarpani'' (present descending half-cycle of cosmic age) was nearing its end, felicities due to ten type of ''[[Kalpavriksha]]'' (wish-fulfilling trees) started declining.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2015|p=7-8}} Fourteen wise men called ''Kulakara'' arose from time to time to teach people how to perform the laborious activities for survival.}} of ''avasarpini''.{{sfn|Jansma|Jain|2006|p=31}}{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1929|p=51-56}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHnXAAAAMAAJ|title=Jainism in South India|isbn=9788185692234|author1=Joseph |first=P. M |year=1997|p=172}}</ref> He taught the men how to cut the ''nabhi'' (navel chords).{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1929|p=55}}

Marudevi, queen of king Nabhi,{{sfn|Jansma|Jain|2006|p=32}} saw the [[Auspicious dreams in Jainism|16 auspicious dreams]]. When she shared her dreams with the king, he explained that she will give birth to a ''tirthankara''.{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1929|p=51}} She then gave birth to [[Rishabhanatha]], the first ''tirthankara'' of present ''avasarpini''.{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2015|p=7-8}}

According to Jain text ''[[Ādi purāṇa]]'', Nabhirāja lived for 1 [[crore]] ''purva'' and his height was 525 ''dhanusha'' (long bows).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2015|p=8}}

